#Let's understand the difference b/w sort() and sorted()

#sort()
#sort() function will modify the list it is called on.
#The sort() function modifies the list in-place and has no return value.

#sorted()
#The sorted() function will create a new list containing a sorted version of the list it is given. 
#The sorted() function will not modify the list passed as a parameter.
#sorted() function will return a list so you must assign the returned data to a new variable. 

#If you want to sort a list but still have the original unsorted version, then you would use the sorted() function.
#If maintaining the original order of the list is unimportant, then you can call the sort() function on the list.

#eg:

vegetables = ['squash', 'pea', 'carrot', 'potato']
new_list = sorted(vegetables)

# new_list = ['carrot', 'pea', 'potato', 'squash']
print(new_list)

# vegetables = ['squash', 'pea', 'carrot', 'potato']
print(vegetables)


vegetables.sort()

# vegetables = ['carrot', 'pea', 'potato', 'squash']
print(vegetables)
